----
-
-vaults and passwords
+title: 1Password implementation
+aliases:
+  - 1Password implementation
+  - 1PASSWORD implementation
+  - how to use 1Password for vault secrets
+tags:
+  - security
+  - secrets
+  - 1password
+date created: Monday, March 30th 2026, 5:17:09 pm
+date modified: Monday, March 30th 2026, 7:40:00 pm
+---
+
+This note gathers the practical steps we follow to implement 1Password as the vault of record for credentials, SSH keys, and automation secrets in **IDAHO-VAULT**.
+
+## Implementation overview
+1Password is the default place for storing SSH keys, API tokens, and other sensitive values needed by the repo. The combination of the [1Password CLI](1Password CLI use cases  1Password Developer.md) and the [1Password SSH agent](1Password SSH agent  1Password Developer.md) keeps secrets encrypted, out of Git, and only provisioned when absolutely necessary.
+
+| Layer | Role |
+| --- | --- |
+| Credentials | Stored in 1Password items and vaults, not Git. |
+| Provisioning | `op` (CLI) provisions secrets via secret references, `op run`, or shell plugins. |
+| Authentication | SSH/Git clients talk to the 1Password SSH agent for key access. |
+
+## Secret management with the CLI
+- Install `1Password CLI` (`op`) and sign in with the account that holds our project vaults.
+- Use the CLI to create or update secrets (`op item create`, `op item edit`, or `op item get`). Keep item titles descriptive, tag them with `idaho-vault`, and place them in dedicated shared vaults so collaborators can grant access quickly.
+- Reference those items from scripts, config files, or CI steps using [secret references](https://developer.1password.com/docs/cli/secret-references/). A reference looks like:
+
+  ```env
+  GITHUB_TOKEN=op://PROJECT/Deploy/GithubToken
+  ```
+
+- When a script runs, wrap it with `op run --` so the CLI injects the referenced secrets into the environment without producing plaintext on disk. For example:
+
+  ```bash
+  op run -- ./deploy.sh
+  ```
+
+  The `deploy.sh` script can read `$GITHUB_TOKEN` as if it were stored in `.env`, but the value never appears in Git.
+- If you need secrets for local development, run `eval $(op signin --output=raw)` and then `op item get ...` to pull them into temporary files or variables. Avoid checking those files in.
+
+See [[1Password CLI use cases  1Password Developer]] for more CLI automation examples and shell plugins that authenticate other tools.
+
+## Injecting secrets into workflows
+- Keep plaintext configs out of the repo—use reference placeholders instead. Example: rename `github.env` to `github.env.ref` and store the real secret in 1Password. Use `op run --env-file=github.env.ref script.sh` to inject the built-in values.
+- CI pipelines (GitHub Actions, etc.) should retrieve secrets via `op run` or by pulling environment variables from secret references using `op inject` instead of storing raw tokens in their configuration files.
+- Document any required vault IDs or items in this note, including who owns them, so collaborators can request access via 1Password.
+
+## 1Password SSH agent for Git & SSH keys
+- Enable the [1Password SSH agent](1Password SSH agent  1Password Developer.md) to keep private keys locked inside 1Password while granting Git/SSH clients seamless access.
+- Follow the steps in the agent doc: turn on the agent, authorize your SSH client, and, if desired, create an `~/.config/1Password/ssh/agent.toml` file to pin specific vaults.
+- If you have more than six keys, add SSH host-specific bookmarks or configure `~/.ssh/config` to limit which key is offered to which host.
+- On Windows, set the `SSH_AUTH_SOCK` environment variable to the socket provided by 1Password so Git operations use the agent automatically.
+- Always authorize each key request when prompted, and configure Touch ID/Windows Hello/biometrics for a smooth workflow.
+
+## Implementation best practices
+- Never commit plaintext secrets, even if they are temporarily stored for testing. If an accident happens, rotate the secret immediately and update the 1Password item.
+- Link this note from `[[TO DO LIST]]` entries that mention __1Password__ so future work references the current implementation plan.
+- When adding new automation (scripts, CI jobs, container configs), update this document with the 1Password items or vaults being used and which collaborators have access.
+- Keep `1Password CLI use cases` and `1Password SSH agent` references as living documents; update their metadata if more detailed instructions are added.
